H0.text: Waxing gibbous is the moon phase that occurs approximately 14 days after a full moon.

H1.text: Waning crescent is the moon phase that occurs approximately 14 days after a full moon.

H2.text: First quarter is the moon phase that occurs approximately 14 days after a full moon.

H3.text: The new moon is the moon phase that occurs approximately 14 days after a full moon.

A4.text: In astronomy, the new moon is the first lunar phase, when the Moon and Sun have the same ecliptic longitude.

A5.text: The astronomical new moon occurs by definition at the moment of conjunction in ecliptical longitude with the Sun when the Moon is invisible from the Earth.

A6.text: The duration from full moon to new moon (or new moon to full moon) varies from approximately 13 days 22+1⁄2 hours to about 15 days 14+1⁄2 hours.

A7.text: The lunar phases progress through the new moon, crescent moon, first-quarter moon, gibbous moon, and full moon phases as the Moon waxes.

A8.text: The eight phases of the moon in order: new moon, waxing crescent moon, first quarter moon, waxing gibbous moon, full moon, waning gibbous moon, last quarter moon, waning crescent moon.

A9.text: The eight phases of the moon in order: new moon, waxing crescent moon, first quarter moon, waxing gibbous moon, full moon.

A10.text: Fingernail moon, a lunar phase waxing until 7 days after or waning since 7 days before the new moon
